Subtyping Analysis

Earlier we gave very broad, general labels to the clusters, but from looking at the article, we see that there are a lot of subtypes for some of the cell types, such as myeloid, T, and fibroblasts. With subtyping analysis, we can look at these cell types in further detail.

We will first be doing this with the fibroblasts as an example.

Subset population

We first subset any cell with the label ‘fibroblast’ and make a new object with only fibroblasts. We can do this with the code below:

fb <- subset(merged_ob, subset = annote_1 == 'fibroblast')
## Warning: Keys should be one or more alphanumeric characters followed by an
## underscore, setting key from umap_harmony_ to umapharmony_

We will then run the main pipeline again on the subsetted object from normalization to cell annotation. We have to do this because we are now looking at subset of cells instead of the whole dataset. We will also integrate with Harmony like we did before because the batch effect will still be present in the raw counts.

Main Pipeline

Normalization

fb <- NormalizeData(fb, verbose = F)

Find Variable Features

fb <- FindVariableFeatures(fb, selection.method = 'vst', nfeatures = 2000, verbose = F)

Scaling

fb <- ScaleData(fb, vars.to.regress = 'nCount_RNA', verbose = F)

PCA

fb <- RunPCA(object = fb, features = VariableFeatures(fb), 
                nfeatures.print = 5, verbose = F)
## Warning: Cannot add objects with duplicate keys (offending key: PC_) setting key
## to original value 'pca_'
# qualitative
# ElbowPlot(object = fb, ndims = 50)

# quantitative 
pct <- fb@reductions$pca@stdev / sum(fb@reductions$pca@stdev) * 100 
cum <- cumsum(pct) 
co1 <- which(cum > 90 & pct < 5)[1] 
co2 <- sort(which((pct[1:length(pct)-1] - pct[2:length(pct)]) > .1), decreasing = T)[1] + 1
pcs <- min(co1, co2) # 14 pcs

# DimPlot(fb, reduction = 'pca', group.by = 'sample_id')

Integration (w/ Harmony)

fb <- RunHarmony(fb, group.by.vars = c('sample_id'), dims.use = 1:pcs, verbose = F)

Transfering Labels

After annotating our new fibroblast clusters, we can transfer the labels to the whole dataset if we wanted to. We can do this with the code below:

# get the new fibroblast labels from the fibroblast object 
x <- FetchData(fb, vars = c('annote_1'))

# find the cell names that were originally called 'fibroblast'
y <- WhichCells(merged_ob, expression = annote_1 == 'fibroblast')

# order the cells from the fibroblast object so they are in the same order in the whole dataset
x <- x[y,,drop=F]

# create a new annotation column in the metadata slot
merged_ob$annote_2 <- as.character(merged_ob$annote_1)

# add the new fibroblast labels to the new annotation column
merged_ob$annote_2[y] <- as.character(x$annote_1)

# plot UMAP with new labels
colors <- scales::hue_pal()(13)
colors <- c(colors[1:2],colors[8],colors[4:7], colors[3],colors[9:13])
DimPlot(merged_ob, reduction = 'umap_harmony', group.by = 'annote_2') + scale_colour_manual(values = colors)

Pathway Analysis

Pathway analysis is a way to analyze groups of related genes between conditions. This helps to interpret large gene lists into biological conditions. There are three types of pathway analyses:

  1. Over-representation analysis (ORA)
  2. Functional class scoring (FCS)
  3. Pathway-topology based (PTB)

For this workshop, we will only be learning how to run ORA and FCS (which we’ll use GSEA). We will be using the clusterProfiler package to run these two analyses. You can look at the manual for more functions:

  • http://yulab-smu.top/clusterProfiler-book/


Before we can actually run analyses, we need to prepare some data.

We first refresh our object (from changes from subtyping) to look at the cell type labels from the ‘annote_1’ column from the metadata slot.

# import object and make sure active identity is 'annote_1'
Idents(merged_ob) <- 'annote_1'
levels(merged_ob)
##  [1] "T"           "acinar"      "epithelial"  "myeloid"     "fibroblast" 
##  [6] "B"           "NK"          "endothelial" "DC"          "RBC"        
## [11] "endocrine"


We will then run DE on cells from a specific cell type between the conditions (N vs. P). We will be running DE on the myeloid cells for this example.

Based on this comparison:

  • positive (+) FC = expressed higher in N
  • negative (-) FC = expressed lower in N
# run DE between N vs. P conditions for myeloid cells
de <- FindMarkers(merged_ob, ident.1 = 'N', ident.2 = 'P', group.by = 'condition', subset.ident = 'myeloid')
## Warning: Keys should be one or more alphanumeric characters followed by an
## underscore, setting key from umap_harmony_ to umapharmony_
de_filt <- de %>% rownames_to_column('gene') %>% dplyr::filter(p_val_adj < .05) %>% arrange(-avg_log2FC)


We will then calculate log2 fold changes between the condition (N vs. P) for myeloid cells. This will output a table of fold changes for all genes found in the object. These fold changes will mainly be used with GSEA.

# calculate log2 fold changes for all genes
## mainly used for GSEA
# ?FoldChange
fc <- FoldChange(merged_ob, ident.1 = 'N', ident.2 = 'P', group.by = 'condition', subset.ident = 'myeloid')
## Warning: Keys should be one or more alphanumeric characters followed by an
## underscore, setting key from umap_harmony_ to umapharmony_
fc <- fc %>% rownames_to_column('gene')


We will then convert gene names to IDs from certain databases (Ensembl, Entrez, ALIAS, etc.). We will be converting gene symbols to Entrez IDs. You could also use gene aliases, but it will give you multiple names for the same gene. Also, make sure you are using the correct species. In this example, we will use the human databases.

# key names for the different IDs
keytypes(org.Hs.eg.db)
##  [1] "ACCNUM"       "ALIAS"        "ENSEMBL"      "ENSEMBLPROT"  "ENSEMBLTRANS"
##  [6] "ENTREZID"     "ENZYME"       "EVIDENCE"     "EVIDENCEALL"  "GENENAME"    
## [11] "GENETYPE"     "GO"           "GOALL"        "IPI"          "MAP"         
## [16] "OMIM"         "ONTOLOGY"     "ONTOLOGYALL"  "PATH"         "PFAM"        
## [21] "PMID"         "PROSITE"      "REFSEQ"       "SYMBOL"       "UCSCKG"      
## [26] "UNIPROT"
# get Entrez ID for all genes
# ?bitr
bitr_df <- bitr(fc$gene, fromType = 'SYMBOL', toType = 'ENTREZID', OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db)
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns
## Warning in bitr(fc$gene, fromType = "SYMBOL", toType = "ENTREZID", OrgDb =
## org.Hs.eg.db): 27.04% of input gene IDs are fail to map...
# add Entrez IDs to fold change and DE tables
fc$entrezid <- bitr_df$ENTREZID[match(fc$gene, bitr_df$SYMBOL)]
de_filt$entrezid <- bitr_df$ENTREZID[match(de_filt$gene, bitr_df$SYMBOL)]

ORA

With ORA, we can find potentially important pathways through the proportion of genes present in certain pathways. We can run ORA on multiple pathway databases, such as GO, KEGG, Reactome, MSigDB, etc. For this example, we will be running the myeloid cells on the GO terms and MSigDB.

The first step is to choose genes that are potentially important. We will use the DE table to find these genes. We will pick the DE genes that are significant between our conditions (adjusted p-value < .05) and have an avg_log2FC >= 1 or <= -1. Picking these thresholds can be subjective, so you can change the p-value or avg_log2FC or create a score based on these two variables. You will need to make two lists: one for upregulated genes (FC >= 1) and another for downregulated genes (FC <= -1).

# get upregulated genes
or_genes_up <- de_filt$entrezid[de_filt$avg_log2FC >= 1 & !is.na(de_filt$entrezid)]
head(or_genes_up)
## [1] "5644" "1208" "5406" "3043" "1504" "1357"
# get downregulated genes
or_genes_down <- de_filt$entrezid[de_filt$avg_log2FC <= -1 & !is.na(de_filt$entrezid)]
head(or_genes_down)
## [1] "64859" "2919"  "3434"  "7503"  "91543" "6648"


After getting the genes, we can run pathway analysis. We are going to run the upregulated and downregulated separately on GO terms first.

# run analysis on GO
# ?enrichGO

## upregulated pathways
or_go_up <- enrichGO(gene = or_genes_up, universe = bitr_df$ENTREZID, OrgDb = org.Hs.eg.db, ont = 'BP', pAdjustMethod = 'BH', pvalueCutoff = 1, qvalueCutoff = 1, readable = T)

There are also functions in clusterProfiler to run KEGG (enrichKEGG()), Reactome (enrichPathway(); need the ReactomePA package), etc. For MSigDB, we can also run on other categories (ex: C1, C2, C3, etc.), which you can change with the msigdbr() function.

GSEA

GSEA is a type of FCS pathway analysis, which it uses gene expression unlike ORA. We can run GSEA on multiple pathway databases, such as GO, KEGG, Reactome, MSigDB, etc. For this example, we will be running the myeloid cells on the GO terms and MSigDB.

The first step is setup the gene list. In GSEA, we want to use all the genes that change in expression between condition (abs(expression) > 0). We could change what we consider as expressed (ex: abs(expression) > 0.5). We also need to order the gene list so that the genes go from most positive FC to the most negative FC. We could use p-values or some other score to order the genes instead if wanted.

# get FCs and order the gene list
gene_list <- fc %>% arrange(-avg_log2FC) %>% filter(abs(avg_log2FC) > 0) %>% dplyr::select(entrezid,avg_log2FC) %>% tibble::deframe()
head(gene_list)

## 4.746314 4.121349 3.675111 3.421446 3.282634 3.056990

There are also functions in clusterProfiler to run KEGG (gseKEGG()), Reactome (gsePathway(); need the ReactomePA package), etc. For MSigDB, we can also run on other categories (ex: C1, C2, C3, etc.), which you can change with the msigdbr() function.

Plots

There are couple of plots that we could use to visualize our pathways. We will only go over a few plots, but other plots can be found in the clusterProfiler manual.

We will be going over 2 types of plots in this workshop. The bar and dot plots can be used for both ORA and GSEA results. Even though there are functions to make these plots in clusterProfiler, they are a bit buggy. Instead we will be using custom code with ggplot() to create these plots.

Bar plot

ORA

# GO (upregulated)
data <- or_go_up@result %>% arrange(-Count)
data <- data[1:10,]

data %>% ggplot(aes(Count, reorder(Description,Count), fill = qvalue)) + geom_bar(stat='identity') + theme_bw() + theme(axis.title.y = element_blank()) 

# MSigDB Hallmark (upregulated)
data <- or_msigdb_h_up@result %>% arrange(-Count)
data <- data[1:10,]

data %>% ggplot(aes(Count, reorder(Description,Count), fill = qvalue)) + geom_bar(stat='identity') + theme_bw() + theme(axis.title.y = element_blank())
